{"title": "Li Fang (diplomat)\n", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li_Fang_(diplomat)", "tags": ["Category:1895 births", "Category:Ambassadors of China to Germany", "Category:Chinese anti-communists", "Category:Chinese collaborators with Imperial Japan", "Category:Chinese diplomat stubs", "Category:Chinese diplomats", "Category:Short description matches Wikidata", "Category:Year of death missing"], "text": "Li Fang (Chinese: \u674e\u82b3; 1895\u2014?) was a Chinese diplomat in the early Republic of China who later joined the pro-Japanese Reorganized National Government of China under Wang Jingwei, serving as its minister in Romania and Hungary. As a commercial attache in Berlin in 1941, he briefly served as the Nanjing regime's interim ambassador to Germany before the arrival of Li Shengwu. A diplomatic capable described him as a close associate of Wang Jingwei, an anti-communist, and a \"friend of Germany's.\"\n\n\n== References =="}